1. What is Java?
Interview Answer : 
      Java is a high-level, object-oriented programming language developed by Sun Microsystems. 
      It is platform-independent because Java code is compiled into bytecode, which can run on any system that has a JVM.
# Real-Time Example
      Suppose a company develops a banking application in Java on Windows. 
      The same application can run on Linux or Mac without changing the code.

2. Why is Java platform-independent?
  Interview Answer
        Java is platform-independent because the compiler generates bytecode instead of machine code.
         The bytecode can run on any operating system that has a JVM.
# Real-Time Example
      You create a Java application on Windows and send the .class file to a Linux machine. 
        It runs without recompilation.

3. What is JVM?
     Interview Answer
         JVM is the runtime engine of Java. It loads, verifies, and 
          executes bytecode and provides platform independence.
# Real-Time Example
      When you run a Java application like an ATM software, 
      the JVM executes the bytecode and displays the output.

4. What is JRE?
Interview Answer
      JRE provides the runtime environment needed to execute Java programs.
       It contains JVM and required libraries but does not contain development tools like the compiler.
# Real-Time Example
     An employee using a Java-based payroll application only needs JRE to run it.

5. What is JDK?
    Interview Answer
         JDK is a complete development package that contains JRE, JVM, and 
          development tools such as the Java compiler. It is used to develop, compile, and run Java programs.
Real-Time Example
         A Java developer writing an e-commerce application uses JDK to compile and test the code.

6.Difference Between JDK,JRE,JVM
 
| JDK                           | JRE                       | JVM                              |
| ----------------------------- | ------------------------- | -------------------------------- |
| Used to develop Java programs | Used to run Java programs | Used to execute bytecode         |
| Contains compiler (`javac`)   | No compiler               | No compiler                      |
| Contains JRE and JVM          | Contains JVM              | Runtime engine only              |
| Used by developers            | Used by users             | Used internally during execution |

One-line answer for freshers :     "JDK is used to develop Java applications, 
                                   JRE is used to run Java applications, and 
                               JVM is the engine that executes Java bytecode. JDK contains JRE, and JRE contains JVM."

6. What is a Class?
 Interview Answer
       A class is a user-defined data type that contains variables and methods. 
        It acts as a blueprint for creating objects.
# Real-Time Example
     A "Car" class can define:
Color
Brand
Speed
All cars are created from the same blueprint.

7. What is an Object?
 Interview Answer
       An object is a real-world entity created from a class. 
        It occupies memory and can access the properties and methods defined in the class.
# Real-Time Example
     If "Car" is a class, then:
BMW Car
Audi Car  are objects.

8. What is OOP?
   Interview Answer
           OOP is a programming paradigm that uses classes and objects to improve code reusability,
           maintainability, and security.
# Real-Time Example
         Banking systems, hospital management systems, and e-commerce applications are designed using OOP concepts.

9. What is Encapsulation?
   Interview Answer
          Encapsulation is the process of hiding data by making variables private and 
          providing public getter and setter methods to access them.
# Real-Time Example
       In an ATM machine, users cannot directly access account balances. They must use authorized operations.

10. What is Inheritance?
  Interview Answer
        Inheritance is a mechanism through which one class inherits the 
         properties and behaviors of another class, improving code reusability.
# Real-Time Example
       A Savings Account and Current Account can inherit common features from a Bank Account class.

11. What is Polymorphism?
  Interview Answer
        Polymorphism allows the same method name to perform different tasks depending on the context.
# Real-Time Example
A payment method:
Credit Card
UPI
Net Banking
All perform payment differently but through the same operation.

12. What is Abstraction?
  Interview Answer
        Abstraction is the process of hiding internal implementation details and 
        exposing only the required features to the user.
# Real-Time Example
       When you drive a car, you use the steering wheel and pedals.
       You don't need to know how the engine works internally.

13. Difference Between = and ==
    Interview Answer
           "=" is used to assign a value to a variable, 
           whereas "==" is used to compare two values or references.
Real-Time Example
int a = 10;  // assignment
if(a == 10) // comparison

14. Why are Strings Immutable?
   Interview Answer
          Strings are immutable to provide security, thread safety, 
          and efficient memory management through the String Pool.
# Real-Time Example
       Passwords, URLs, and database connection strings should not be modified accidentally.

15. Difference Between == and equals()
  Interview Answer
        For objects, == compares memory locations, whereas equals() compares actual object contents.
# Real-Time Example
Two users enter the password "admin".
Even if stored in different objects, equals() checks whether the text is the same.
